SIMPLE: scope
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: -scope
<hw>-scope</hw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>. <ety>[Gr. <grk>skopo`s</grk> a watcher,
spy. See <er>Scope</er>.]</ety> <def>A combining form usually signifying
<xex>an instrument for viewing</xex> (with the eye) or
<xex>observing</xex> (in any way); <as>as in micro<ex>scope</ex>,
tele<ex>scope</ex>, alto<ex>scope</ex>,
anemo<ex>scope</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scope</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Scope
<hw>Scope</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[It. <ets>scopo</ets>,
L. <ets>scopos</ets> a mark, aim, Gr. <grk>skopo`s</grk>, a watcher,
mark, aim; akin to <?/, <?/ to view, and perh. to E. <ets>spy</ets>. Cf.
<er>Skeptic</er>, <er>Bishop</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>That at which
one aims; the thing or end to which the mind directs its view; that
which is purposed to be reached or accomplished; hence, ultimate design,
aim, or purpose; intention; drift; object.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Shooting wide,
do miss the marked <xex>scope</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Your <qex>scope</qex> is as mine own,⟦br⟧
So to enforce or qualify the laws⟦br⟧
As to your soul seems good.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>scope</qex> of all their pleading against man's
authority, is to overthrow such laws and constitutions in the
church.</q> <rj><qau>Hooker.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Room or opportunity for free outlook or aim; space
for action; amplitude of opportunity; free course or vent; liberty;
range of view, intent, or action.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Give him line and <qex>scope</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In the fate and fortunes of the human race, <qex>scope</qex> is
given to the operation of laws which man must always fail to discern the
reasons of.</q> <rj><qau>I. Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Excuse me if I have given too much <qex>scope</qex> to the
reflections which have arisen in my mind.</q>
<rj><qau>Burke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>An intellectual cultivation of no moderate depth or
<qex>scope</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Hawthorne.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Extended area.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧The
<xex>scopes</xex> of land granted to the first adventurers.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Sir J. Davies.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Length; extent; sweep; <as>as, <ex>scope</ex> of
cable</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- Scope, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To look at for the purpose of
evaluation; usually with <ptcl>out</ptcl>; <as>as, to <ex>scope out</ex>
the area as a camping site</as>.</def> -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scopeline</ent>⟦br⟧
